  "slug": "panforte-siena",
  "title": "Panforte",
  "subtitle": "Dense Sienese fruit and nut cake spiced with pepper and cinnamon",
  "excerpt": "Panforte is a flat, dense Italian confection from Siena: dried fruit, nuts, spices, and honey bound with a little flour and egg white, baked until set. It is not a cake in the sponge sense; it is closer to a thick slab of spiced fruit and nut brittle. Serves in thin wedges and keeps for weeks.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Panforte (literally 'strong bread') is a medieval Sienese confection documented in Italian domestic cooking references from the thirteenth century. The modern form, using dried figs, nuts, spices, honey, and a little flour, appears in Italian domestic cookbooks of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries and is widely documented in English-language translations of Italian regional cooking guides. Ada Boni, Il Talismano della Felicita (1925), documents the Sienese panforte tradition. The basic technique and ingredients are public-domain and widely reproduced in English-language baking references.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Panforte is a confection from Siena, not a cake in the sponge sense. The texture is dense, chewy, and slightly sticky, with the fruit and nuts clearly visible in each slice. It keeps for several weeks wrapped in baking paper. Slice it paper-thin and serve with coffee or a small glass of something sweet."
          }
        ]
      },
